  "prompt": "Mobile Phones: When I think about someone, he or she texts me right away or sometimes they call me. Is it the waves from the phone that make me think about him/her or what?",
  "response": "What you're describing is a common experience where you think about someone and then they reach out to you shortly afterward. While it feels almost magical, there\u2019s no scientific evidence to suggest that mobile phone waves or any form of telepathy are responsible for this phenomenon. Here\u2019s a breakdown of what might be happening:\n\n1. **Subconscious Awareness**:  \n   You might already have some subtle cues or patterns in your relationship with that person. For example, you might know their routine, interests, or when they\u2019re likely to contact you, even if you\u2019re not consciously aware of it. This can make it seem like you predicted their call or text.\n\n2. **Confirmation Bias**:  \n   Humans tend to notice and remember events that confirm their beliefs or expectations. When you think of someone and they contact you, it feels significant. But you likely don\u2019t notice all the times you think of someone and they don\u2019t reach out.\n\n3. **Coincidence**:  \n   Sometimes, these events are simply coincidental. With so many interactions and thoughts happening daily, it\u2019s statistically likely that some of these occurrences will align.\n\n4. **Emotional Connections**:  \n   If you\u2019re close to someone, your thoughts about them might coincide with times when they\u2019re naturally more likely to contact you (e.g., after a shared event, during a holiday, or during a routine time they usually reach out).\n\nAs for mobile phone waves, they are part of the electromagnetic spectrum used for communication, but they don\u2019t have any known ability to influence thoughts or create telepathic connections. The explanation for your experience is more likely rooted in psychology and coincidence rather than technology or physics.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
